Durban - A high-speed chase between police, a security company and suspected armed robbers in the Pietermaritzburg CBD resulted in a crash and the arrest of two women on Tuesday. Mi7 National Group spokesperson Colin Davids said, the Mi7 Special Threat Response Unit teams spotted a police vehicle in pursuit of a white Mercedes and joined the high-speed chase to assist the police bring the vehicle to a stop on Tuesday at around 11pm. “The driver of the suspected vehicle entered a residential area in the lower CBD, where he lost control and crashed into an embankment bordering the N3 highway,” he said. Davids said three men fled the wreckage and escaped arrest. “Two women were found in the vehicle; both of whom were arrested,” he said. He said it is believed the suspects were allegedly involved in a string of armed robberies, targeting pedestrians or students. Describing the events that led to the high-speed chase, Davids said police were patrolling the Woodlands area when a victim flagged them down. He said the victim reported that the three men had just robbed him at gunpoint, while the women sat in the car laughing. Police got a description of the vehicle and spotted it nearby when the chase ensued, he said. “Not only did the vehicle have fake number plates, but inside, three cellphones were found, a number of bank cards, and a number of student cards. One firearm, a revolver, was also recovered inside the vehicle,” said Davids. The SAPS were approached for comment but did not respond at the time of publishing.    THE MERCURY